agency_name: Coconino County Sheriff’s Department (Arizona)  or Coconino County Public Health Services District Medical Examiner Office (Arizona) 1-928-679-877
circumstance: On October 31, 1958, the skeletal remains of an unidentified female were located approximately 10 miles southeast of the Grand Canyon in Coconino County, Arizona.  She had reddish/brown hair that had been dyed to a lighter brown color.  A white wool short-sleeved cardigan, brown, green and red plaid Capri pants (“Graff California Wear” brand), white rayon underpants and a “Maidenform Alloette” white cotton bra (size 34 C) were located near the remains.  In addition, the following personal items were located: a gold chain, a small jar of Ponds cold cream, a white nylon comb, a small white powder puff with traces of sun-tan colored powder and a small blue plastic nail file case with the indentation of the letter “P” and a hand printed capital “R” written next to it.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Coconino County Sheriff’s Department, reference case number 509-01397 or the Coconino County Public Health Services District Medical Examiner Office, reference case number 12-064.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Jackson County Sheriff’s Office  (Oregon)  or Jackson County Medical Examiner’s Office (Oregon) 1-541-774-3840
circumstance: On July 11, 1963, the body of an unidentified child was recovered from the Keene Creek Reservoir along Highway 66 approximately 12 miles east of Ashland, Oregon. Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed the child died some time after October 1962.  The child was wrapped in an aqua blanket and a handmade patchwork quilt with red gingham squares. Two iron assayer’s molds were also found wrapped in the quilt.  The child may have suffered from Downs Syndrome or another congenital illness. The child was found wearing a red long-sleeved shirt with horizontal thin white stripes, gray corduroy pants with an elastic waist and a buckle for size adjustment, ankle socks and size 3 white shoes known as "Jumping Jacks".  The clothing was likely purchased at “JC Penney”.  It is believed the shoes were purchased at Norris Shoe Store in downtown Medford, Oregon.  He was also wearing a cloth diaper with blue diaper pins that was covered with elastic pants.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Jackson County Sheriff’s Office, reference case number 63-23011 or the Jackson County Medical Examiner’s Office, reference case number 08-14146.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Delaware State Police (302) 741-2728 or Delaware State Medical Examiner’s Office (302) 577-3420
circumstance: On March 18, 1967, this unidentified, Caucasian female's body was found off the shoulder of Porter Road, a rural area in Bear, New Castle County, Delaware.  This location is just a few miles away from Interstate 95 and US Highway 40. She was approximately 16-25 years old, with long, curly, dark brown hair, and brown eyes.  She was petite in stature; height 5'2"; weight 110 lbs.  With reasonable certainty, her bra size is estimated to be 34DD.  Her ears were pierced, but it did not appear she had worn earrings in quite a while.  She had a vaccination scar on the front of her left thigh; no other scars or distinguishing marks were observed.  Her teeth contained several restorations, and were in very good repair, suggesting that she had seen a dentist within a year prior to her death.  Recent ancestry testing suggests she may be of European, Italian, Greek, or Jewish descent. Her legs were stuffed inside a large cloth commercial laundry bag, which was determined to be from a laundry and dry cleaning company, located in Trenton, New Jersey.  She was found wearing only a pair of blue bikini panties, and a red ribbon, which tied her hair back. She was transported in a vehicle from an unknown location, quite possibly from another state, and tragically dumped along the side of the road.  It is estimated that she died March 17 – 18, 1967, within 24 hours of being found.  The above image, suggestive of what she may have looked like in life, is a reconstruction prepared by a NCMEC Forensic Artist, based upon morgue and crime scene images.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Alameda County Coroner (California) 1-  Oakland Police Department: 1-510-238-3821
circumstance: On October 2, 1969, the body of an unidentified female was discovered in a room of the St Louis Hotel off 7th Street in Oakland, California. It is believed the Jane Doe had been deceased less than 24 hours. The decedent had short brown hair and a slim build, and was found with a white knit dress on. Also found with the decedent was a white sweater, white knee-height leather boots, multicolored (pink, green, orange, purple) bell-bottom jeans, multicolored (yellow, grey, orange, brown, black) blouse, and a multicolored (black, white, orange, yellow striped) miniskirt dress. The decedent also had a removable dental plate for a dental extraction of the front upper central incisor tooth. The decedent also had needle scars on the insides of both elbows.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Alameda County Coroner, reference case number 69-2266, or the Oakland Police Department, reference case number 6966670.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Galloway Township Police Department (New Jersey)  and New Jersey State Police Office of Forensic Sciences 1-609-584-5054
circumstance: On December 6, 1971 an unidentified female was found in Galloway Township, New Jersey near the Garden State Parkway. Her body was found in a wooded area off Jimmie Leeds Road. The female had been deceased for several months prior to being found. The female is estimated to be 12-18 years old but likely on the younger side closer to age of 12-14. She was petite at about 5’02” tall and around 115 pounds. Her hair was possibly auburn and  shoulder length. She was found wearing a blue polo shirt, bell bottom slacks with multiple colored vertical stripes, and brown leather sandals. She also wore a wide leather band bracelet with small brass eyelets all around the band. Attached to the bracelet through some of the eyelets was a small watch. The watch did not appear to have been originally attached to the leather band but secured separately. Inside the female’s pants was a key to a local motel along the Garden State Parkway. The images above is an enhanced photograph of the bracelet the female was wearing along with a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what she may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On July 11, 1971, the skeletal remains of an unidentified female were found approximately 50 feet down an embankment off the Angeles Crest Highway, ¼ mile west of the Red Box Canyon Ranger Station in Montrose, California. Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed she could have been deceased for up to one year prior to recovery.  She had kinky hair that was described as "multicolored" (red, brown and black). She had long manicured fingernails and a gap between her upper front teeth which would have been noticeable to her family and friends. She was found wearing an orange/yellow skirt with a 27" waist and 34" hip, a full 34", a white slip with lace trim, a white short sleeve turtleneck sweater, and white socks. Based on her clothing sizes, she may have appeared tall and thin.  She was also found wearing a yellow metal 1957 "Bulova" brand ladies watch (shown above). The watch had a yellow metal expansion band with a broken link and bore serial number T556641.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 717384.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: This unidentified female was found on February 19, 1971 in Sumter County, Florida. She was found in the water under the Lake Panasoffkee Bridge along Interstate 75. It is estimated that she had been deceased for several weeks. The Jane Doe was 17-25 years old at the time of her death. She stood between 5’00”-5’05” tall and weighed about 110-120 pounds. She had long straight brown hair. She was found wearing plaid green pants, a matching green shirt and a shawl with a green and white print. She also wore a gold ladies Baylor wrist watch and a yellow gold ring with a clear stone on her left ring finger. She also wore a thin gold chain necklace. An anthropological exam of her bones revealed that she had an orthopedic surgery to her right ankle, most likely within a few years prior to her death. Additionally, periostitis was found on her lower right leg in the process of healing. This might have caused her some pain or discomfort. A dental examination of her teeth revealed that she had extensive dental work completed. She had several fillings and a porcelain crown on one of her top middle teeth. Forensic testing of her teeth and hair determined that this female was a foreigner that arrived in the United States from between a year and 2 months before her death. The analysis determined that this female is likely from southern Europe, possibly Greece. The above images were completed by the Forensic Anthropology Department at the University of South Florida. One is a facial reconstruction of what the female may have looked like in life. The second is a composite of the clothing she was found wearing.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Oklahoma Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (Oklahoma) 1-  or 1-405-239-7141
circumstance: On June 26, 1972, an unidentified male pedestrian was involved in a fatal accident when he was struck by a vehicle near the I-40 overpass on Highway 183 in Clinton, Oklahoma. He had long brown hair, just above his shoulders in length. He also had unshaven faint hair growth along the sides of his cheeks. He was wearing a blue double-knit shirt ("Never Iron brand" by CAMPUS), blue jeans with a brown leather 30-inch belt with “Captain’s” buckle, tall brown leather boots (size 9-9.5) with 1 inch closing strap and brass rings on either side and a blue armband on his left arm made of denim material. Also found with the decedent was a pack of cigarettes (“MARLBORO” brand) with a St Louis, Missouri stamp #42289, a white-gold colored promise ring with “TC968” engraved on the inside,  and a sheet of paper with dates June 16 through June 30 suggesting that the subject was employed by a company or location called Mollincrodt/Mellincrodt/Mallinckrodt.   Anyone with information should contact the Oklahoma Office of the Chief Medical Examiner and reference case number 721300.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: St. Petersburg Police Department Homicide Unit (Florida)
circumstance: On June 9, 1973, this unidentified child was pushed in front of a moving vehicle in St Petersburg, Florida, and died at the scene. The female was estimated to be between 14 and 16 years of age. She was new to the area and had been in town for only a few weeks prior to her death. She had dark auburn hair and distinctive blue eyes. Her ears were pierced but the hole on her right earlobe had closed up so she wore a pair of earrings on her left earlobe. Her front tooth was chipped, but it is not clear whether the chip was present prior to her death or if she sustained that injury during the accident. Her fingernails were chewed and very short. The female was using several names thought to be aliases including Janice Marie Brock, Marie, Maria and Cindy. Most people knew her as Marie. She is also believed to have friends or family in Virginia and possibly North or South Carolina. The St. Petersburg Police Department's case number is 73-46184, and the Medical Examiner's case number is 73-1084. The image above is a facial reconstruction completed by a Forensic Artist with the Medical Examiner’s Office.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On September 5, 1973 the skeletal remains of an unidentified female were located in a hilly area along a rural fire access road southeast of Skyline Drive in La Habra Heights, California. Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed the date of death was approximately 30 to 90 days prior to the discovery. She had shoulder-length light brown hair. She was found wearing a blue/green turtleneck long-sleeve sweater (size large), a blue, pink and yellow halter hop, light blue corduroy pants with “S-J” on the right rear pocket (size medium, shown above), and blue tennis shoes with white soles (size 6). She had pierced ears and was found wearing gold metal earrings with peace symbols and blue stone insets (shown above). Her fingernails were painted orange.  Dental records indicate she may have had two teeth (lower molars) extracted within 4-6 months of her death.  The photos shown above have been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 1973-14553.

agency_name: Harris County Institute of Forensic Sciences (713)796-6858
circumstance: On August 9, 1973, the skeletal remains of an unidentified male were recovered in Houston, Texas. Based on the condition of the remains, the decedent was likely deceased for 12 months or more prior to recovery. The decedent was white, possibly with Hispanic admixture.  He had brown hair approximately 7 inches in length (from the crown). He was found with belted “Catalina” swim trunks with vertical red, turquoise, gold, and dark blue stripes, with the letter “C” on the silver buckle (shown above) and a khaki-colored long sleeved t-shirt that tied in the front. The shirt had a large blue and white peace symbol and the letters “USMC”, and “L84MF” written underneath the peace symbol. He was also found with dark blue corduroys with a 32 inch waist and a 30 inch inseam, a knotted leather ankle bracelet, and brown leather cowboy boots that were 12 inches in length and had the word “NEOLITE” on the heel.  Examination revealed that the boy had a mild form of spina bifida which may have caused him lower back pain or possibly affected his stride; however, it may not have produced any noticeable symptoms. John Houston Doe is the last known unidentified victim of Dean Arnold Corll, aka “The Candy Man”, who abducted and murdered at least 29 young males in the Houston area between 1970 and 1973. The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what he may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Harris County Institute of Forensic Sciences, reference case number ML73-3356.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Marin County Coroner’s Division (California)  or Mill Valley Police Department (California) 1-415-389-4100
circumstance: On June 20th, 1974, the skeletal remains of an unidentified child were discovered along the 100 block of Country Club Drive in Mill Valley, California. Based on the condition of the remains, the child had likely been deceased approximately 2 years prior to discovery. The child was considerably small for their age. The child was found wearing a child-size olive-green hooded ski coat, a blue sweater, a green-striped shirt, and blue T-shirt. Also found with the remains was a red “ladybug” stick pin. The child had a gray-blue discoloration on their teeth, possibly due to the use of antibiotics or tetracyclines.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Marin County Coroner’s Division and reference case# 74-0215, or the Mill Valley Police Department and reference case# 74-1468.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On September 13, 1975, the body of an unidentified female was found on the 700 block of Artesia Boulevard, an industrial area in Compton, California.  It is believed she died only hours prior to the discovery of her body.  She was found wearing a gold metal ring with a large black stone.  Within the black stone was a gold colored flower.  She was also wearing a white metal ring with one black stone and one white stone, a white metal chain necklace and one white metal bracelet.  She had short black hair and a 1-1/2"scar on the instep of her left foot.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 7511050.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Hillsborough County Sheriff’s Office  or Hillsborough County Medical Examiner’ Office (Florida) 1-813-914-4567
circumstance: On September 23, 1975 a partial skull was found in Thonotosassa, Hillsborough County, Florida. The skull was located in an orange grove on Timmons Road near a cemetery. Forensic analysis determined that the skull belongs to a white female, between the ages of 17-25. Several teeth were not accounted for as her mandible and right maxilla were not recovered. From the few teeth that remained, it appeared she had received some dental care during her life as a filling was seen in her first upper left molar.  The image above is a facial reconstruction of the female provided by Hillsborough County Medical Examiner’s Office.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: Hunters located the skeletal remains of this Jane Doe on February 14, 1975 in Maury County, TN. Her body was found in a wooded area off Joe Brown Road, about 2 miles north of Highway 99. It is estimated that she died 6-9 months prior to being found. This places time of death in the Spring through early Fall of 1974. Bones of a puppy were also found near the Jane Doe. She is 15-25 years old. She is estimated to have stood around 5’04" tall and weighed 132 pounds. She had black hair. The Jane Doe had healed rib fractures from a previous injury that occurred earlier in life. No evidence of cavities or restorations were found in the recovered teeth but she did have an extra tooth on the top right side of her jaw. A red shell blouse, flowered blue slacks, a bra, female underpants, and black Italian made wedge shoes were found with her remains. The images above were created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist. It is a reconstruction of what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: San Mateo County - Office of the Coroner (California)
circumstance: In October, 1975 the victim was found in Huddart Park in San Mateo County, CA. The victim is a Caucasian male estimated to be between 9-12 years old. It is believed he had been deceased between 1-3 years at the time he was found, placing his death possible between the years of 1972-1974. The victim stood about 4’07" - 5’00" tall. Brown hiking boots (image to the left) were found on the victim’s feet. A dark blue sweater/jacket with snaps were found near the body and a wooden cross (image to the right) was also found in the area. The victim’s teeth revealed significant decay suggesting the child had poor or no dental care prior to his death. The San Mateo County Coroner’s case number is #75-936.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: An unidentified female was found on December 20, 1976 in White Haven, PA in Carbon County. She was found along Lehigh River under a bridge on Interstate 80. She had been deceased about 24 hours. The female was in her third trimester of pregnancy when found. Her race is undetermined and could be Caucasian, Asian, Native American or of mixed ancestry. There is a possibility that she is of European decent such as Polish, Czech, or Silesian. The female is estimated to be 14-25 years old. She stood between 4’11” and 5’04” tall with dark brown hair and brown eyes. She had a 2 inch scar on her left leg, just above the heel, a small circular mole above her left eyebrow, and a mole on her left cheek. The moles on her face could have developed sometime during her pregnancy. A dental exam revealed she had four molars extracted, likely prior to the age of 12. Sometime after the extractions, she had several cavities restored. At some point after that it appears she did not receive or seek any further dental care, evidenced by a visible fracture and decay found on other teeth that could have caused her pain. The images above are facial composites created by forensic artists that depict what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On April 11, 1976, the remains of an unidentified female were found in a dry creek bed in a rural area approximately 90 feet west of Lopez Canyon Road in San Fernando, California. Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed the Jane Doe was likely deceased one week prior to discovery. She was approximately 20 years of age with a small build and was estimated to have weighed between 100-120 lbs. The decedent was found wearing purple bell-bottom pants (“MALE” brand), a tan long sleeve multicolored print blouse worn midriff-style with rust-colored tree figures and elastic cuffs (“STYLED IN CALIFORNIA” brand). She was also found with black 4” heel clog shoes with a heavy leather strap and a brown suede jacket with a white wool collar and white cuffs (“LONDONTOWN BY CHECKPOINT” brand). She had dirty blonde roots to light brown hair approximately 18 inches in length that reached her middle back and plucked eyebrows. The decedent had a full silver cap on left upper first molar. She also had a vertical scare below her right knee cap approximately 1” in length.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 76-4631.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: This unidentified female was found off the roadway in the 5600 block of Dogwood Road near Lorraine Park Cemetery in Baltimore County, Maryland. It is estimated that she died a few days prior to being discovered. The female is estimated to be in her late teens or early twenties. She has shoulder length brown wavy hair.  She has a dark, olive skin complexion. A homemade tattoo was found on her upper right arm, near her shoulder, of initials that appear to be JP but may also be JS, JD, JB -or- SP, SS, SD, SB. She also has a one and half inch scar on her left thigh and her ears are pierced. Her teeth were well taken care of. All four third molars had been extracted. The unidentified female was found clothed, wearing a light white and beige short sleeved sweater, Levi brand beige and yellow jeans, a white bra, brown leather shoes with soft rubber composition soles, and a rawhide string necklace with a turquoise blue bead, as shown above. Inside her pant pocket two keys were found on a safety pin. One key was used for a night latch and the second appears to be a house key. The unidentified female may have been from, spent some time in, or had associates or family in the state of Massachusetts. The composite images above were created by a NCME Forensic Artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Metro Nashville Police Department (Cold Case Unit, Case #76-47535) (615)880-2928
circumstance: On March 24, 1976 the female victim was found in the Harpeth River in Davidson County, TN. The decedent had been deceased less than 24 hours. She is a Caucasian, Hispanic or Native American female between the ages of 14 to 17 years old. She had long black straight hair and stood about 5’02” tall. She was found wearing a necklace with beads and a white dove on it. She had a mole on her left temple and old scars on both arms which may have come from cigarette burns. Prior to her death the victim was hitchhiking with another Caucasian female. The girls stated that they were heading to Haines City, FL to visit the companion’s family. The female companion was described to be around the same age with sandy blonde hair and wore wire rim glasses, but was never located or interviewed regarding this decedent. The girls mentioned that they had just ran away from an institution up north that would have treated substance abuse and mental health problems. The decedent’s name may be Sherry or Cheryl.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On August 14, 1977, the remains of this unidentified female were found in Everett, Snohomish County, Washington. The victim was estimated to be between 15 and 21 years of age, and may have been 5’10” in height. She is believed to have been killed on August 9, 1977. Her killer stated that he picked the victim up while she was hitchhiking. She had short, lighter brown hair with no color treatment, appeared to have a suntan, and was wearing a halter top, cut-off jeans with a pack of “Marlboro” cigarettes in the pocket, a Timex watch with a leather strap and yellow metal face, and blue/white “Mr. Sneaker” brand tennis shoes-men’s size 7. Some of the victim’s clothing is pictured. She had two restorations to her upper front teeth. The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like. The additional photos have been enhanced to aid in visual identification and may not reflect the original case file images. Anyone with information should contact the Snohomish County Sheriff’s Office and reference case number 77-17073.

agency_name: New Jersey State Police Major Crimes Unit  and New Jersey State Police Office of Forensic Sciences 1-609-584-5054 x5656
circumstance: An unidentified female was found on February 28, 1977 in Middlesex County, New Jersey. Her body was found just off the NJ Turnpike near the Molly Pitcher Commuter Bus ramp in Cranbury Township. She had been deceased for a few days. The female is 15-21 years old. She stood approximately 5’07” tall and weighed around 125 pounds. She had black kinky hair. The female had several slight gaps in between her top front teeth.  She was found wearing an Indian print hooded wool coat, a striped cowl-neck sweater, blue Levi jeans, pantyhose, and beige healed shoes, size 9B. The investigation revealed that the shoes were purchased at a store in Brooklyn, New York. The female also wore several pieces of jewelry. She wore a Seiko watch with a black band on her left wrist with a gold ring with a small heart on her left ring finger and another gold ring with a clear stone on her left middle finger. She wore a gold twisted bracelet on her right wrist along with a silver ring with a rose on her right middle finger and another gold ring of an interlocking design on her right ring finger.  The female had long fingernails that were polished along with her toenails. She was also possibly a smoker. The image above on the left is a facial composite drawing completed by a Forensic Artist with the NJSP and depicts what the female may have looked like in life. The images on the right displays the pieces of jewelry and the shoes that are described above.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Marion County Sheriff’s Office (Florida)  or District 5 Medical Examiner’s Office (Florida) 1-352-326-5961
circumstance: On March 22, 1977 an unidentified deceased male was found in a small clearing surrounded by heavy palmetto leaves, trees and bushes near Longwood Street in Summerfield, FL. He may have been deceased for up to a year before being found. The male's age is estimated at 17 - 25 years old with a height and weight of 5’5" and 165 pounds. His race is unknown. The male was wearing a red long-sleeved shirt with white buttons; black trousers with a zipper; black patent leather belt with a white metal buckle with a round stone in the center; and black boots with a side zipper.  The male was also found with a rose colored comb. The images above are of the belt buckle and a facial reconstruction provided by the Medical Examiner’s Office which depicts what the male may have looked like in life.

circumstance: On April 20, 1978, the body of an unidentified female was found buried in a commercial flower field in the 19300 block of South Wilmington Avenue in Carson, California.  She had long black hair and a medium complexion. Her fingernails were short and painted pink and her ears were pierced.  Her eyebrows were thin and appeared well-groomed. Her upper teeth overlapped on the right side which would have been obvious to those who knew her. She had a 3 ¼-inch vertical scar on her abdomen above her belly button and light stretch marks, indicating she possibly had a child.  Two Hispanic males were seen driving away from the site where the decedent’s body was found in a 1970 dark blue Vega Hatchback.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner’s Office, reference case number 785116.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Lake County Sheriff’s Office (Florida)  and District 5 Medical Examiner’s Office (Florida) 1-352-326-5961
circumstance: On October 8, 1978 an unidentified deceased female was found floating in the water of Lake Harris about one-tenth of a mile north of the south end of the Howey Bridge. Lake Harris is located in the Lake Harris Recreation Area in Leesburg, FL. It is estimated she had been deceased for days.  The decedent was a black female, believed to be approximately 16 - 18 years old. She is believed to have been approximately 5'4" - 5'5" tall and weighed 100 - 120 pounds. She had cropped black hair and brown eyes. Her ears were pierced, but she was not wearing earrings. Her fingernails were extremely short with red polish on both her fingernails and toenails. Her teeth were in good repair. The images above were provided by the Medical Examiner’s Office and depict what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Office of the Chief Medical Examiner, North Carolina
circumstance: An unidentified female was found on June 2, 1978 near Lumberton in Robeson County, North Carolina. The female was found at the edge of a cornfield along Highway 74 approximately 1 mile east of Interstate 95. The female had been deceased 2 to 4 weeks prior to being found. She was between the ages of 15-22 years old. She stood around 5’03” tall and weighed between 95-110 pounds. She had light brown or reddish brown medium length hair. The female was found wearing blue jeans with slightly ragged cut-off hems, a white hooded short-sleeve shirt with multicolored horizontal stripes through the center, and white wedge-type open toed shoes with a flower design on the top. Both her fingernails and toenails were painted metallic red. The female had seen a dentist during her life. She had several fillings and had four molars extracted, leaving small gaps between her back teeth on the top and bottom of her mouth. The first two images above were completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the female may have looked like in life. The two images above on the right are the shirt and shoes the victim was found wearing.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: An unidentified female was found on June 17, 1978 in Blytheville, Mississippi County, AR. Her body was found along Interstate 55 near exit 57 for Highway 148/Burdette. She had been deceased for only a few hours prior to being found. Witnesses last saw her alive earlier that same day at a restaurant in Blytheville. The female was with a male companion around her same age. The male companion’s body was also found that same day, approximately 15 miles north along Interstate 55 in Pemiscot County, Missouri. Both subjects remain unidentified. The female is estimated to be between 18-25 years old. She stood about 5’02” tall and weighed approximately 125 pounds. She had light brown hair, 4-6 inches in length. She had a non-professional tattoo on her upper right arm of the name “Kim.” She was found clothed wearing a multi-colored striped blouse, blue jeans and she wore a silver chain necklace with a mercury dime pendant with a hole in it. The image above was completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and is a reconstruction of what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: San Diego Medical Examiner’s Office:  San Diego County Sheriff’s Office: 858-974-2457
circumstance: On February 14, 1978, the remains of an unidentified female were found next to the pavement of Proctor Valley Road in the rural area of Otay, San Diego County, California. Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed the decedent had been deceased for approximately 2 days. The decedent was found wearing a white halter top with a blue flower pattern, and blue denim overalls. The decedent had extensive dental work completed, including a root canal on the lower front right incisor, which was also cracked in half. She had brown hair of shoulder length that was styled in a ponytail and tied with a rubber band. The decedent had pierced ears, and her right ear was malformed and slightly smaller than her left ear. She is believed to have had brown eyes.  The reconstructions featured above are an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the San Diego County Medical Examiner’s Office, reference case number 78-338 or the San Diego County Sheriff’s Office, reference case number 543957.

circumstance: On June 3, 1978, the body of an unidentified male was found lying on the pavement of Division Street, half a block east of Corona Street in Long Beach, California. It is believed the John Doe had likely been deceased less than 24 hours prior to discovery. The decedent had a 3/8 inch scar half an inch above his right eyebrow. He had a slim build with fair skin, and brown hair that extended just below his ears. He was found wearing a light blue T-shirt-size 42-44, blue jeans (“LEVI” brand), a brown leather belt, blue socks, and blue and white tennis shoes with brown soles (“REDWING” brand). The deceased also had a faint stamp on the back of his hand that read “PAID”.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like. circumstance: On December 28, 1978, the skeletal remains of an unidentified male were discovered along I-40 East approximately 306 feet East and 108 feet south of mile marker 196. The decedent was found wearing a dark colored sweater, blue jeans (“LEVI’S” brand), and brown leather lace-up shoes with rubber soles (“BEE JAYS” brand). He had a silver filling on one of his upper right molars. He was also found wearing 3 necklaces, including one with a silver cross on a long silver chain and one of the “Capricorn” Zodiac sign. circumstance: An unidentified male was found deceased in Putnam County, Georgia on June 10, 1978. He was found inside a train car carrying coal at the Georgia Power Plant in Eatonton. The investigation revealed that the train originated in Fariston, KY on June 8, 1978 and made stops in Corbin, KY, Etowah, TN, Atlanta, GA, and Warren County, GA before stopping in Eatonton on June 10, 1978. It is unknown in which city the male entered the train car. It’s estimated that he had been deceased for 1-2 days prior to being found. The male is described as African American, 15-20 years old. He had black hair styled in an afro. Some of the hair was dyed a reddish tint. His height and weight are unknown but he’s described to be well nourished and thin build. The male had long fingernails on both hands and curled eyelashes. He also had sutures in his left upper lip which was still unhealed from a recent injury when he was found. Numerous old scars were also seen on his upper chest, back and legs. The male was found wearing blue jeans with a blue elastic belt with the word “jeans” inscribed on it. He also wore a black t-shirt and a type of gray leather, lace-up dress shoe approximate size 8. The image above is a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC forensic artist and depicts what the male may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: The Jane Doe was found in Caledonia, NY on November 10, 1979. She was found in a cornfield by a passing motorist along Route 20. It is estimated that she died within 24 hours from the time she was found. She had short brown wavy hair which appeared to have been recently frosted and was in the process of growing out. She had several small scars over her body. She had freckles on her shoulders and had acne on her face. Both of her ears were pierced but she was not wearing any earrings. An exam of her teeth suggested that within 1-2 years prior to her death she may have suffered from discomfort and possibly severe pain in her mouth from untreated cavities. This may have caused her difficulty chewing on one side of her mouth or she may have showed outward signs of discomfort. She also might not have showed any discomfort. She was tanned and had visible bikini lines. She was wearing tan corduroy jeans, multi-colored plaid shirt, blue knee socks, brown shoes (size 8) and a red windbreaker jacket. She also wore a silver beaded necklace with 3 small turquoise birds around her neck and a silver keychain with a heart bearing the inscription “He who holds the key can open my heart” and a key that fits into the corresponding heart, around the front belt loop of her pants. The investigation has found that the victim likely grew up or spent some time in Arizona, California or Florida before coming to New York.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On July 8, 1979, skeletal remains of two unidentified children were found near Highway 20, west of Willits in Mendocino County, California.  It is believed the children had been deceased 6-8 months prior to the recovery of the remains.  Both children are believed to have been between 10 and 20 years of age, likely between 12 and 16.  The female child was found with the pictured earring which is described as a hoop with a perched bird (pierced-ear type).  The earring was possibly handmade from shell material.  DNA testing has confirmed the children are not maternally related.  The photos featured above are an artist’s rendering of what the victims may have looked like.  The Jane Doe is listed in NCIC under U765178400 and in NamUs under UP 10447.  The John Doe is listed in NCIC under U765181075 and in NamUs under UP 10450.  NCMEC has an active case on the Jane Doe under case number 1103861 and an active case on the John Doe under case number 1103864.  Anyone with information should contact NCMEC or the Mendocino County Sheriff’s Office, reference case number 79-1900.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On August 14, 1979, the body of an unidentified female was found in a vacant parking lot near the intersection of Las Vegas Boulevard South and Sahara Avenue in Las Vegas, Nevada. Her hair was wavy and shoulder-length.  Her ears were not pierced. Her fingernails and toenails were well manicured and painted red.  She was found wearing blue jeans and a blue linen button-up shirt with embroidered designs/sequins and a tie at the waist (shown above).  She was also wearing a plain white gold ring on her right index finger and two white gold necklaces, one having a small silver cut-out leaf pendant with a small turquoise stone and the other with a white gold chain and clear plastic heart pendant (shown above). circumstance: On September 4, 1979 a deceased white female was found in a parking lot at the Biscayne Garden Apartments off NW 2nd Avenue in Miami. The female had noticeable facial acne and old burns on the inside of each calf that she possibly received from a motorcycle exhaust pipe. The female had seen a dentist in life as several dental fillings were seen in her teeth. She was wearing a white t-shirt, yellow floral scarf, and long blue jeans. circumstance: An unidentified female was found on June 20, 1979 down an embankment between the Eastbound lanes of Route 22/322 and the Juniata River in Watts Township, Pennsylvania. She had been deceased for several months up to one year. She is estimated to be 15-30 years old and stood around 5’06” tall. She had blonde to light brown medium length, possibly curly hair. A healed rib fracture was found suggesting the female endured an injury earlier in life. A dental exam revealed several silver fillings and evidence that she had an upper molar extracted during her late teenage years. The female was wearing a tan button up long sleeve shirt with two breast pockets, one that zippered close. Underneath she wore a blue tank top with another white lace-like blouse with three-quarter length sleeves. She also had on blue twill slacks with red thread and red and green argyle knee-length socks. A pair of white shoes with buckles were also found near her body. The female was also found wearing several pieces of jewelry including two elongated turquoise rings, a black ribbon onyx ring, a heavy silver chain bracelet (Avon brand), teardrop turquoise stud earrings, and a thin chain necklace with a turquoise pendant. Images above are of a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist suggesting what the female may have looked like in life. The other images depict the shoes and some of the jewelry recovered with the victim.
org_name: National Center for Missing & Exploited Children

circumstance: On November 2, 1979, this unidentified male was struck and killed by a car driven by a drunk driver. The victim had been walking northbound on Interstate 95 at the Commercial Boulevard exit in Fort Lauderdale at the time he was struck. He was estimated to be in his late teens or early twenties. He stood around 5’05” tall and weighed 208 pounds. The victim may have had a mustache. He had no dental work completed. He was wearing a shirt, trousers, and socks (no further description available). The victim was with another male who was also struck and killed but was later identified. circumstance: On July 17, 1980, the remains of an unidentified female were discovered in a heavily wooded area, one mile south of South Eklutna Lake Road near mile post two in Eklutna, Alaska. The decedent was also found wearing the following items of jewelry:  a copper and turquoise bracelet, turquoise and brown shell necklace with heart pendant, twisted metal loop earrings that are gold in color, a white shell ring with brown inset ring, and a ladies chain-linked wrist watch with gold plate and brown face (“TIMEX” brand). Matches were also found in the pocket of the jacket (“SALEM” brand). This unidentified female is a known victim of serial killer Robert Hanson, who murdered 17-21 women around Anchorage, Alaska between 1971-1983. circumstance: On April 9, 1983, skeletal remains of an unidentified male were discovered along the northbound lanes of the 605 freeway in Santa Fe Springs, California (Los Angeles County).  Based on the condition of the remains, it is believed he had been deceased between 1-12 months at time of discovery. The decedent had a medium to slight build, and was found wearing the following: a T-shirt with “Halbert’s Corner Liquor, Alhambra, Calif.” written on it (“Hi-Cru by Steadman” brand, size 38-40), brown leather high top work boots with crepe soles, a green cotton jacket, a tan military-style web belt and brass buckle, and dirty grey cotton work pants with a 30-inch waist.  Investigation has revealed the jacket and pants were from a local uniform rental company.  A nose inhaler and a hair brush were also located with the decedent.  The images featured above are an artist’s rendition of the John Doe’s clothing.  Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner, reference case number 83-04561.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Indiana State Police  or Newton County Coroner’s Office 1-219-285-2515
circumstance: An unidentified deceased male was found on October 18, 1983 in a wooded area off US-41, a half a mile north of SR-10 in Newton County, Indiana. He had been deceased for several months prior to being found. The unidentified male was approximately 5’11” tall, his weight is unknown but appeared to be of average build. He had short black hair. He was found wearing Levi blue jeans with a red and white belt with the word “Devil” written several times around it and a gold buckle with the word “Jeans” on it. He was also wearing size 10 Hush Puppy boots with a side buckle. The unidentified male had seen a dentist at some point in his life as several dental fillings were identified in his teeth. The investigation revealed that this male was possibly hitchhiking earlier that summer in July, 1983 in Terra Haute, Virgo County, Indiana. The image above is a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the male may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Indiana State Police  or Newton County Coroner’s Office 1-219-285-2515
circumstance: An unidentified deceased male was found on October 18, 1983 in a wooded area off US-41, a half mile north of SR-10 in Newton County, Indiana. A Forensic Anthropologist determined he was between 17-23 years old and stood approximately 5’05” tall. His weight could not be determined. He had medium length wavy reddish brown hair. He had two non-professional appearing tattoos on his right forearm. On the inside of his forearm he had a small cross with two dashes above it. On the opposite back side of his right forearm he had a small rectangular or U shaped design. The male had severely fractured his nose earlier in life and also fractured his left ankle. The male had dental work completed as several dental fillings were seen in his teeth. Staining was also found on his teeth suggesting possible tobacco use. He was found wearing brown slacks, size 30x30 and brown leather, lace up hiking boots. The first three images above is a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depicts what the male may have looked like in life. The image on the right is a photograph of the tattoo found on his inner right forearm.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: An unidentified female was found on July 4, 1984 in Warren County, Kentucky. The skeletal remains were found along the northbound lanes of Interstate 65, approximately 2.5 miles south of Bowling Green. It is estimated that she had been deceased for several months up to two years prior to being found. The female is 12-16 years old. She stood between 4’9” and 5’00” tall and weighed between 90-115 pounds. She had brown hair and was possibly right handed. The female had a healed lesion on the rear of her skull that was possibly a result of a previous injury. She had seen a dentist prior to her death as she had several fillings and displayed hypoplasia on her two bottom middle teeth. She was wearing a multicolored long sleeve pullover shirt and red corduroy pants. The images above were created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and represents what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Lake County Sheriff’s Office (Florida)  or District 5 Medical Examiner’s Office (Florida) 1-352-326-5961
circumstance: On April 18, 1984 an unidentified white female was found off a dirt road in the Lake Dorr Recreation Area of Ocala National Forest. She had been deceased 2 - 4 weeks before being found. She is estimated to be between 17 - 20 years old, 5’00” – 5’01” tall and approximately 100 pounds. The female's hair was light brown, fine, and straight. Her left ear was pierced but she was not wearing an earring. It is unknown if her right ear was also pierced. She may have broken ribs that healed during her lifetime. She was missing two upper teeth; some of her remaining teeth were discolored reddish-purple. Her fingernails were painted coral or orange color. The female was wearing Wrangler blue jeans, waist 24”, a long night shirt or beach wear with printed flowers and the words “Have You Kissed Your Child Tonight” on the front, a black T-shirt with “Here comes trouble”, and tan canvas slip-on shoes with blue trim. The female also wore a 15” metal necklace chain. At the time of the initial investigation, detectives were told the female was new to the area. The image above on the left is a facial composite provided by the Medical Examiner’s Office and depicts what the female may have looked like in life. The image above on the right is an enhanced image of the shoes she was found wearing.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On May 2nd, 1984, the remains of an unidentified child were discovered on the pavement of Glendora Mountain Road, approximately 150 feet north of mile marker .33 in Glendora, California. Based on the condition of the remains, the child had likely been deceased approximately one year prior to discovery. The child is believed to be male however the gender was not able to be definitively determined.  The race was either white or a mixture of white and Asian.  The child had short, dark brown straight hair, approximately 1 ½-2 inches in length. The child was also likely to be closer to 3-4 years of age. The child likely suffered from hydrocephalus.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the child may have looked like.   Anyone with information should contact the Los Angeles County Coroner’s Office, reference case number 1984-5656.

agency_name: North Carolina Office of Chief Medical Examiner  or Jackson County Sheriff’s Office 1-828-586-4480
circumstance: An unidentified male was found on February 12, 1984 in the mountains of Jackson County, North Carolina. His body was found near the Thorpe Reservoir Dam in an area known as Pine Creek. It’s estimated that he had been deceased about a month prior to being found. The male is between 15-20 years old. He stood about 5’09” tall at 171 pounds with light brown hair. He was found wearing blue jeans, a plaid blue long sleeve shirt, brown jacket with a front zipper, tennis shoes and white socks. His teeth were in good condition showing no signs of dental care. The unidentified male had been in the local area for at least three months going by an alias. It’s possible that he spent time in Florida, Tennessee, and Illinois and had been employed as bus boy in some of those states. The image above is a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist of what the person may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: New Hampshire State Police Major Crime Unit
circumstance: On November 10, 1985 two unidentified females were found near an overturned 55 gallon metal barrel on a wooded trail adjacent to Bear Brook State Park in Allenstown. One of the females is an adult believed to be 22-33 years old. She had light brown, fine wavy hair. She had several dental fillings and 3 teeth had been removed. The second female was a child, 5-11 years old. Both of her ears were doubled pierced. She had no dental fillings. She may been ill at the time of her disappearance as the autopsy revealed evidence of pneumonia in one of her lungs.  DNA testing confirms that these two females are maternally related. On May 9, 2000 two additional unidentified female children were found inside a 55 gallon metal barrel in the same area where the first bodies were discovered 15 years earlier. One female was 2-4 years old. She had no dental restorations but she did have a noticeable overbite.  The other female was the youngest of the victims at 1-3 years old. She had no dental restorations but did have a slight gap between her upper two front teeth. This youngest child was also determined to be maternally related to the first two victims found in 1985. The 2-4 year old has not yet been biologically linked to the other victims. No clothing or jewelry were found with the victims. It is estimated that all four have been deceased for the same amount of time and died prior to 1985. Images above are facial reconstructions completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Tennessee Bureau of Investigation (615) 744‐4000 or Forensic Anthropology Center, University of Knoxville (865) 974-4408
circumstance: On April 3, 1985 partial skeletal remains of a young female were located near Big Wheel Gap Road, four miles southwest of Jellico in Campbell County, Tennessee. A pair of hiking boots (size 5) and a necklace made of plastic buttons were found near the remains but it is unknown if they belonged to the female. agency_name: Tennessee Bureau of Investigation 1-615-744‐4000 or Forensic Anthropology Center, University of Knoxville (Tennessee)
circumstance: An unidentified female was found on January 1, 1985 in Campbell County, Tennessee. She was found down an embankment off the shoulder of  the southbound lanes of Interstate 75 in La Follette. The female had been deceased for several days. She is estimated to be 17-25 years old. She stood approximately 5’02" and weighed 110 - 115 pounds. She had shoulder length reddish curly hair, freckles, and both of her ears were pierced twice. She had several scars. One healed burn scar the size of a silver dollar was seen on the inside of her left arm. She also had scars on her forehead near the hairline, on her left and right knee and a scar on her right hand. The female was approximately 10-12 weeks pregnant at the time of her death and there was evidence she had recently given birth to another child. She also wore a removable partial dental plate for two upper central teeth that had likely been in place for at least 9 months before her death. She was found wearing men’s blue jeans and a beige velour top. The image above is a facial composite completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artists and depicts what the female may have looked like in life.

agency_name: Tampa Police Department (Florida)  / Hillsborough Medical Examiner’s Office 1-813-914-4500
circumstance: An unidentified female was found deceased on February 6, 1986 in Tampa, Florida. Her body was found along 2nd Ave between 31st and 34th street in an industrial area of Tampa. She had likely been deceased three to eight weeks prior to being found. The female is estimated to be 16-22 years old. She stood approximately 5’02” tall. She was African American and had “kinky brown hair” according to the original police report. An anthropological exam revealed that the female had sustained injuries to the left side of her head and nose earlier in life which likely caused her to have a deviated septum. Several congenital defects were also seen in her spine but it is unknown whether they would have caused her any physical discomfort. The female may have even been unaware of the defects. The female’s teeth were in very poor condition and some of the untreated teeth were likely causing her pain. Forensic testing has suggested the female was most likely born and raised in Florida.  The images above are various angles of a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and depict what the female may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

agency_name: Ontario, California Police Department (California)  or 1-909-395-2742 or San Bernardino County Sheriff’s Department (California) 1-909-387-2978
circumstance: On Thursday, August 21, 1986, the body of an identified male was found in an abandoned house on Holt Blvd in Ontario, California. He is believed to have died between August 15 and August 18, 1986. He had a fair complexion and had two fine scars, about 1" long, running horizontally across the front of his chin. He had light brown hair, approximately 2 inches in length.  He would have had a very distinctive smile, as his upper left central incisor (the left of his two front teeth) was missing, possibly from birth - leaving a gap. He still had his wisdom teeth. He did not appear to be in poor health or undernourished.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the John Doe may have looked like. circumstance: An unidentified female was found deceased on January 24, 1988 in Bensalem, Pennsylvania. Her body was found on the old Publicker Distillery property off State Road near the Delaware River. She had been deceased for several years prior to being found. The female is approximately 16-21 years old. She was petite standing around 5’00”-5’01” and weighing 100-120 pounds. The female was also six months pregnant. An exam of her teeth revealed that she had poor dental health. Two lower back teeth had been extracted earlier in life possible due to severe decay. She was possibly subjected to facial trauma that resulted in severe tooth loss of her upper three front teeth that might have been noticeable in life. The female also had a slight open bite. The female was found clothed in designer “Braxton” jeans, a purple lace camisole, a white patterned dress, and black mesh stockings. Two rings were found with the female. Two different pairs of shoes were found. One was a black leather open toed platform shoe and the second pair was a grey leather high heeled pump. circumstance: On December 15, 1988, the body of an unidentified male was found in a culvert under a bridge off County Road 22 (now known as Eldorado Parkway at approximately the 9100 block), ½ mile east of FM 289 in Frisco, Texas (Collin County). The decedent is believed to have been deceased for approximately 24 hours at time of discovery. He had straight black hair, approximately 3 ½ inches in length, and a faint black mustache above upper lip.  The decedent was found wearing a black motorcycle jacket, a short sleeve grey and white striped shirt, green-grey corduroy jeans, a black belt with a red/black/gold buckle, grey socks, and black loafer shoes (“Italians” brand, size 5). He was found wearing the following jewelry:  two black rubber rings on his left ring finger, a yellow to gold colored watch on left wrist, and a red and green string style bracelet also on his left wrist. The decedent was also found with a disposable lighter, a pack of cigarettes (“Marlboro Light” brand), and chapstick in the pockets of his jacket. He had scars on his left forearm, right forearm and on his chest.  He also had two tattoos: the first on his upper left arm of a heart with a cross and arrow through the heart with letters “R y A” in the middle (possible translation to “R and A” in Spanish, shown above), the second tattoo is a cross on the front of the left forearm. His top right central incisor tooth is also outlined in a silver cap. The photo featured above is a computer generated image (provided by the Texas Rangers) of what the John Doe may have looked like. circumstance: An unidentified male was found on November 10, 1988 in Caroline County. The male was found in a wooded area along Interstate 95 near the Ladysmith Road exit. He was found fully clothed wearing a blue & gray short sleeved t-shirt(boy’s size large), blue denim jeans (with 30” waist) with the cuffs folded up to shorten the length, and red & black cowboy boots (size 8 ½ D). The boots had minimal wear and appeared to be in new condition. The male had all four third molars missing. The teeth could have been extracted earlier in life or congenitally absent. Another body of an adult male between the ages of 35-45 was found with this young male. The adult male is also unidentified. Forensic testing has suggested that both males are paternally related, but their specific relationship is unknown. circumstance: On August 7, 1994, the remains of an unidentified female were discovered in a vacant dirt parking lot 60 feet north of La Tuna Canyon Road, approximately ½ mile east of the 210 Freeway in Sunland, California. The decedent was likely Hispanic, but may have been an admixture with Caucasian or Asian, and had a larger build that was considerably heavy for her size. She had black, shoulder length hair. The decedent had a ¾ inch horizontal scar on her right forehead, as well as many various small moles covering the entirety of her forehead. She had extensive dental work, including at least ten fillings and restorations, with various crooked teeth and gaps that would have been apparent when she talked. She was found wearing a multi-colored flower print blouse, brown pants (“LEVI’s" brand), two yellow metal earrings-one in each ear, a yellow metal ring with a single stone on left her ring finger, a yellow metal chain with attached Jesus figure, and a brown wig (“NEW BORN FREE” brand). She was also found with tennis shoes (“LA GEAR” brand), a math book, and a rubber band tying her hair back. The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the Jane Doe may have looked like. circumstance: On September 28, 1995 an unidentified female was found behind a shopping plaza on Hartford Road in New Britain, CT. It is estimated that she had been deceased less than 2 weeks prior to being found. The female is estimated to be between 17-20 years old and had brown hair that was styled up and held in place with bobby pins and an elastic ponytail holder. She had a pierced naval and was wearing a silver naval ring. Both ears were also doubled pierced. The female was found clothed wearing a long sleeve brown and beige striped pullover shirt (Croquet, size small), white bibbed overalls (Union Bay, size small), white socks, and brown shoes (LA Gear, size 6 ½ ). Additionally she wore a gold herring bone necklace, a ring with a pink stone, and a Gitano brand watch. The female has been connected to an adult Jane Doe recovered in Tolland, MA about a week later on October 6, 1995. DNA testing revealed that these unidentified females share a mother-to-daughter relationship. This adult female is estimated to be 30-45 years old. She wore maroon prescription eyeglasses and had partial upper and lower dentures. She wore several rings, a gold Sergio Valente wristwatch and her ears were pierced. The investigation has revealed that the females likely resided or frequented the upstate New York area around Albany. The far left image above is a facial reconstruction completed by  a NCMEC Forensic Artist depicting what the female may have looked like in life. The middle two images are of the ring and naval ring the young female was found wearing. The image to the far right is a composite of the adult female provided by the Massachusetts State Police.

circumstance: An unidentified female was found deceased on march 5, 1996 in a wooded area off Falls Road in Baltimore County, Maryland. She had been deceased for several years. The female is approximately 17-19 years old. She stood between 5’01”-5’04” tall. Her weight, hair and eye color cannot be determined. circumstance: This unidentified boy was found on September 25, 1998 in Mebane, Orange County, NC. It is estimated that he had been deceased at this location for several months. The child’s race is either White or Hispanic. He is estimated to be 10-12 years old and around 4’11" tall. He had straight brown hair. The boy had no dental fillings but some teeth had preventative sealant placed on them to help prevent cavities and decay. circumstance: An unidentified male was found on May 28, 1998 in Gadsden, Alabama. The body was found by fisherman in the Coosa River near the Dub Parker Boat docks in the water. His hair color, eye color and weight are unknown. No clothing or jewelry were found with his body. His lower jaw and some upper teeth were not recovered. No dental fillings were seen on any of the recovered teeth. Four of his upper teeth had been fractured prior to death. The fractures could have been a result of an accidental traumatic injury or from using his teeth as a tool, for example, to open a bottle. The images above were created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and are of a facial reconstruction of what the victim may have looked like in life. circumstance: On October 9, 1999 the body of an unidentified female was found in Yuma, Arizona, near the Colorado River and Avenue 3 ½ E in an area known locally as “The Tree”.  The female victim is believed to be Caucasian and between 15 and 22 years of age. Her hair was light brown with red highlights, waist-length and worn in two long braids. Her right ovary was missing and may have been surgically removed.  She had a surgical scar on her lower right abdomen and a partially finished “Angel Baby” tattoo on the outside of her right ankle (shown above). She wore two stud earrings in each ear, one on the lobe and one at the mid-point of each ear.  She was wearing two pendant necklaces, one of a half-moon and stars and the other contained the words “Our Lady of Mt. Carmel” (shown above). She was wearing a short-sleeved white cotton pullover shirt with two butterflies on the upper left chest area, green sweatpants and black sneakers. circumstance: An unidentified deceased boy was found on February 26, 1999. His body was found in a wooded area behind a small church cemetery on Clifton Springs Road in South Dekalb County, Georgia. The boy had been deceased for several months before he was found. He is estimated to be 5-7 years of age. He stood approximately 4’00” tall and weighed about 50 pounds. He was found wearing a long-sleeve hooded pullover shirt made of two different materials. The body of the sweater was blue and white plaid and the arms and hood were dark blue thermal material. He was also wearing blue jeans and size 11, Timberland brown suede boots. Advance forensic analysis has suggested that the child is from the local region which encompasses Dekalb County, the Atlanta area, South Georgia and possibly into Northern Florida. The image above on the left is a facial reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist. The image on the right is a clay reconstruction completed by an FBI Forensic Artist. Both images depict what the child may have looked like in life.

agency_name: New Hampshire State Police Major Crime Unit
circumstance: On November 10, 1985 two unidentified females were found near an overturned 55 gallon metal barrel on a wooded trail adjacent to Bear Brook State Park in Allenstown. One of the females is an adult believed to be 22-33 years old. She had light brown, fine wavy hair. She had several dental fillings and 3 teeth had been removed. The second female was a child, 5-11 years old. Both of her ears were doubled pierced. She had no dental fillings. She may been ill at the time of her disappearance as the autopsy revealed evidence of pneumonia in one of her lungs.  DNA testing confirms that these two females are maternally related. On May 9, 2000 two additional unidentified female children were found inside a 55 gallon metal barrel in the same area where the first bodies were discovered 15 years earlier. One female was 2-4 years old. She had no dental restorations but she did have a noticeable overbite.  The other female was the youngest of the victims at 1-3 years old. She had no dental restorations but did have a slight gap between her upper two front teeth. This youngest child was also determined to be maternally related to the first two victims found in 1985. The 2-4 year old has not yet been biologically linked to the other victims. No clothing or jewelry were found with the victims. It is estimated that all four have been deceased for the same amount of time and died prior to 1985. Images above are facial reconstructions completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: An unidentified deceased female was found on November 5, 2001 in Atlanta, Georgia. She was found in a vacant lot locals used to discard debris on Griffin Street. circumstance: On April 27, 2002, the body of an unidentified female was found behind a business in the area of 1850 East University Drive in Tempe, Arizona. circumstance: An unidentified female was found on March 25, 2003 in Alcoa, Tennessee. The female’s skeletal remains were found along a creek in a small wooded area off Cusick Road near the Knoxville airport. It is estimated that she had been deceased anywhere between 8 months to 4 years. The female is 17-25 years old. She stood between 5’04”-5’10” tall. Small black synthetic braids were found near her body and thought to have belonged to her. The female’s teeth showed two unique characteristics. Two of her upper front teeth were missing prior to her death for several years. The remaining upper front teeth showed extreme flaring and would have been extremely protruded, sticking almost straight out. The female’s lower jaw was not recovered and characteristics of her bottom teeth are unknown. It was estimated that he was in his late teens to very early twenties, stood between 5’1” and 5’3” tall, and weighed 135 lbs.  Earlier in life, the male had broken his nose and right big toe.  The male had two homemade stippled tattoos.  One of them was on his left hand between his thumb and pointer finger and depicted the letters “UL”.  The other tattoo which was found on his forearm was illegible.  The male was found wearing a black short sleeved shirt with the letter “Z” and a Starter Brand logo on the front. The shoes had blue accents and had blue and white soles with the word “Flight” written on the side.  A red BIC lighter was also found in the male’s pocket.  An anthropological assessment of his bones showed that he may have had poor nutrition or chronic sickness during childhood, and he may have been a migrant worker who grew up outside of the United States. agency_name: Fond Du Lac County Sheriff’s Office Tip Line
circumstance: On November 23, 2008 an unidentified female was found deceased in Fond du Lac County. She was located in a small creek near an abandoned farm off Skyline Drive, which is about 1 mile, North of Highway 28 and East of Interstate 41. It is estimated that she had been deceased for several months prior to being found and likely died during the Summer or Fall of 2008. The Jane Doe is 15-21 years old and thought to be Caucasian, but Hispanic and Native American cannot be ruled out. She had long light brown to dark blond hair. She stood between 4’10”-5’04” tall and weighed between 110-135 pounds. Her teeth were in good condition with good alignment. She had fillings in four of her bottom molars. Anthropological examination also revealed that she had Spina Bifida Occulta, but possibly never knew she had this condition. It is also suggested that she might have been knock kneed or pigeon toed, where her feet turned slightly inward. A well healed fracture to one of her left ribs was also found suggesting she suffered some type of injury earlier in life. The Jane Doe was found wearing a black shirt (size small) and jeans (size 3) as pictured above. The clothing was most likely purchased at a Family Dollar Store or general retailer. The first three images above are a reconstruction completed by a NCMEC Forensic Artist and shows what the female may have looked like while alive.

The remains are believed to be those of a Hispanic female.  A “Tallino” brand jacket (size M, shown above) and a shoe (“76”, “Z” or “Zeta” brand, shown above) were located with the remains.  The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the decedent may have looked like. circumstance: On March 14, 2009, the partial skeletal remains of an unidentified male were found under thick brush located near the intersection of Surona Road and Palmetto Road in Wimauma, Hillsborough County, Florida. He had been deceased less than 5 years. The male is believed to have been between 12 and 16 years of age at the time of his death. An anthropological assessment revealed that the decedent was of Guatemalan or Hispanic/Mexican-American ancestry and may have been involved in heavy labor or agricultural work in life. The boy was found wearing “Ice Pole” brand jeans with “Ice Pole USA” spelled out in yellow & black letters running vertically down the pant legs. Attached to one of the pockets by a metal chain was a black leather wallet with the word “Choppers” engraved. An image of the wallet is pictured above.  The image above on the left is a facial reconstruction created by a NCMEC Forensic Artist to show what the male may have looked like in life.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On December 29, 1989, the body of an unidentified female was found on the stairs to a building located at 5433 Westheimer Street, Houston, Texas. She was found wearing black corduroy pants (“LEE” brand - Size 10M), a white pullover t-shirt, black socks, and black shoes (“COASTER” brand). She also had a small, half-moon shaped scar on her right knee and a 1 inch scar on her right forearm. The reconstruction featured above is an artist’s rendering of what the decedent may have looked like.  Anyone with information should contact the Houston Police Department and reference case number 12165089 or the Harris County Institute of Forensic Science and reference case number ML89-8294.
org_name: NCMEC-Unidentified

circumstance: On 09/18/2003 at approximately 1:30 a.m. Anne Arundel County Police responded to the 1700 block of Severn Tree Blvd., Severn, MD, in reference to a shooting and possible abduction.  Officers determined that Lamarst Porter had been shot and abducted.  Porter was last seen in the company of two balck males who are believed to have forced Porter into his 1991 Lincoln Mark VII bearing Maryland Tag: L J T 0 3 3 and fled the area.  Evidence at the scene indicates that Porter was fatally injured.  Porters vehicle was recovered in the Glen Burnie area a few days after the incident. Lamarst's body has never been located.  The case is still active, and Detectives are seeking information from the public on additional witnesses or suspects in this case.
org_name: Maryland Center for Missing Children
